my. Yet for every scholar who survived and thrived, many, many more did not. To be hired by an American university, a refugee scholar had to be world-class and well connected, not too old and not too young, not too right and not too left, and, most important, not too Jewish. Those who were unable to flee were left to face the horrors of the Holocaust. In this rigorously researched book, Laurel Leff rescues from obscurity scholars who were deemed “not worth saving” and tells the riveting, full story of the hiring decisions universities made during the Nazi era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030024905740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300249057423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300249057/original  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles